io.zbox.zboxfs

Class OpenOptions

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.zbox.zboxfs.OpenOptions
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AutoCloseable

    public class OpenOptions
extends Object
    Options and flags which can be used to configure how a file is opened.

    This builder exposes the ability to configure how a File is opened and what operations are permitted on the opened file. The Repo.openFile(String) and Repo.createFile(String) methods are aliases for commonly used options using this builder.

    Generally speaking, when using OpenOptions, you'll first call OpenOptions(), then chain calls to methods to set each option, then call open(Repo, String), passing the path of the file you're trying to open. This will give you an opened File instance that you can further operate on.

    Example

    Opening a file for both reading and writing, as well as creating it if it doesn't exist.

     File file = new OpenOptions()
     .read(true)
     .write(true)
     .create(true)
     .open(repo, "/foo.txt");
    See Also:
    File

      • append

        public OpenOptions append(boolean append)
        Sets the option for the append mode.

        This option, when true, means that writes will append to a file instead of overwriting previous content. Note that setting .write(true).append(true) has the same effect as setting only .append(true).

        Parameters:
        append - append flag
        Returns:
        this open option

      • versionLimit

        public OpenOptions versionLimit(int limit)
        Sets the maximum number of file versions allowed.

        The version limit must be within [1, 255], default is 1. It will fall back to repository's RepoOpener.versionLimit(int) if it is not set.

        This option has no effect for directory.

        Parameters:
        limit - limit on maximum number of file versions
        Returns:
        this open option

      • dedupChunk

        public OpenOptions dedupChunk(boolean dedup)
        Sets the option for file data chunk deduplication.

        This option indicates whether data chunk should be deduped when writing data to a file. It will fall back to repository's RepoOpener.dedupChunk(boolean) if it is not set.

        Parameters:
